id: impacted
title: tnl impacted — path-to-unit mapping
scope: feature
owners: [@jana]
paths: [src/impact.ts, src/commands/impacted.ts, src/index.ts]
surfaces: [tnl impacted]
dependencies: [parser, cli-skeleton]

intent:
  `tnl impacted <path>...` returns the TNL units whose declared `paths:`
  overlap with any of the given code paths. `repo-wide` units are
  always included. Matching is structural — no fuzzy strings or glob
  patterns. Consumed by agents directly at the CLI and by the MCP
  server (A3 wraps this as `get_impacted_tnls`).

behaviors:
  - The module MUST expose `getImpactedTnls(queryPaths: string[], options?: { cwd?: string }): ImpactedTnl[]` where each `ImpactedTnl` carries exactly: `id`, `title`, `sourcePath`, `scope`.
  - The CLI MUST register an `impacted` subcommand via the default registry; `src/index.ts` MUST import the command module.
  - The CLI MUST accept one or more positional path arguments. Zero positional paths MUST exit 2 with a usage message on stderr.
  - Path overlap between a query path Q and a TNL path T MUST be defined as: Q equals T, OR T is a directory prefix of Q (Q starts with T + `/`), OR Q is a directory prefix of T. Trailing slashes on either side MUST be handled consistently.
  - Every TNL with `scope: repo-wide` MUST appear in the result regardless of query paths.
  - A TNL with `scope: feature` MUST appear in the result iff at least one of its declared `paths:` entries overlaps with at least one of the query paths.
  - Results MUST be ordered deterministically: `repo-wide` units first (sorted by `id`), then `feature` units (sorted by `id`). No duplicates.
  - The CLI MUST print one `id` per line on stdout and exit 0 (including the zero-match case, which prints nothing).
  - When the `tnl/` directory does not exist in the invocation CWD, the CLI MUST print an error telling the user to run `tnl init` first and exit 2.
  - When any `.tnl` file under `./tnl/` fails to parse, the module MUST propagate the parse error (fail fast; malformed contracts are a user-fixable error, not a silent skip).
  - The module MUST NOT invoke an LLM, make network calls, or depend on any runtime package outside Node's standard library.
  - Tests MUST cover: exact path match; directory prefix in both directions (query-is-dir-of-TNL-file, TNL-is-dir-of-query-file); non-overlap yields no feature match; `repo-wide` unit always included; multiple query paths union correctly; deterministic ordering (repo-wide first, then alpha by id); empty query paths → exit 2; no `tnl/` directory → exit 2; malformed `.tnl` file under `./tnl/` → exit 2; zero-match CLI exits 0 with empty stdout.

non-goals:
  - Glob patterns in query paths (`src/**/*.ts`) — deferred.
  - Matching against `surfaces:` (CLI commands, routes, MCP tools) — deferred; A2 scope is `paths:` only per the phase plan.
  - Reading the sidecar; `impacted` reads `.tnl` files directly via the parser.
  - JSON output mode — the MCP server (A3) exposes the programmatic form. CLI stays plain-text.
  - Excluding units based on any attribute other than `paths:` and `scope:`.

rationale:
  Why include repo-wide units unconditionally: a repo-wide TNL (like
  `workflow.tnl`) applies to every session by definition. Agents asking
  "which TNLs cover my edit" need the repo-wide rules in every answer.

  Why fail fast on a malformed `.tnl` rather than skip: a parse error
  means the contract in that file is currently invalid, and downstream
  tools (resolver, verifier, MCP) would miss it silently otherwise.
  Surfacing the failure here pushes the user to fix the broken file.

  Why one id per line on stdout: composes trivially with shell
  pipelines (`tnl impacted src/foo.ts | xargs tnl retrieve` once
  retrieve lands in A3). Programmatic consumers use the MCP server.
